## 12. CODING STANDARDS

- **Every HARD gate control must show a clear, prominent UI block** â€” red banner, disabled button with tooltip, or full-screen gate message. Never silently fail.
- **No work-arounds for control gates** â€” do not add "skip" buttons, overrides, or dev bypasses in production code
- **Supabase RLS** must be enabled on all tables â€” never query as service role from the client
- **Error handling** â€” every Supabase query must have try/catch and user-facing error messages
- **Loading states** â€” every async action needs a loading indicator
- **Offline support** â€” mechanic screens should handle poor connectivity gracefully (queue actions locally if possible)
- **TypeScript interfaces** â€” define a type/interface for every DB entity
- **Comments** â€” add a comment referencing the Control ID (e.g., `// L-02: One active job enforced`) wherever a control is implemented

---

## 13. WHAT IS OUT OF SCOPE

Never build or suggest:
- Payroll processing
- Full ERP replacement
- Asset procurement systems
- HR management
- Customer SLA management
- Any bypass of the Control Matrix gates

---

## 14. DESIGN PRINCIPLES (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

> "If the job data is correct, all reporting, billing, and audit outcomes are correct."

- Job = commercial unit. Vehicle = context. Never conflate them.
- Extra work = new job = new PO. Always. No exceptions.
- One mechanic = one active job at a time. Always.
- No PO â†’ no work. No approval â†’ no extra work. No invoice/payment â†’ no vehicle release.
- AI output never overwrites original data (notes, photos, voice).
- Closed and invoiced records are immutable.
